sentences: William "Sonny" Criss (23 October 1927 – 19 November 1977) was an American jazz musician.
His first major break came in 1947, on a number of jam sessions arranged by jazz impresario Norman Granz.
In 1956 he signed to Imperial Records, based in New York, and recorded a series albums including Jazz U.S. A , Go Man!
Capitol, which owned the master recordings, reissued them as a double-CD set on their Blue Note imprint in 2000.
Prestige signed Criss in 1965, and he continued to record well-acclaimed albums which were mainly rooted in hard bop traditions.
By 1977, Criss had developed stomach cancer and did not play again.
As a consequence of this painful condition, Criss committed suicide (self-inflicted gunshot) in 1977, in his adopted city of Los Angeles.
On June 25, 2019, The New York Times Magazine listed Sonny Criss among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the 2008 Universal fire.
